            <td><img src="udla.gif" alt="UDLA - P" height="89"
 width="90"> </td>
            <td>My first extended visit to Latin America (besides an
overnight stay in Ensenada) was a <a
 href="http://webhost.bridgew.edu/phayesboh/Mexico/Cholula.htm"> summer
in
Mexico</a> with my wife Pamela, mostly at the <a
 href="http://www.udlap.mx/"> University of the Americas
Puebla</a> . We wrote a photo essay about our trip in the Fall 1991
issue of Focus,
the magazine of the American Geographical Society.</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      </center>
      <table width="100%">
        <tbody>
          <tr valign="top">
            <td><br>
My first home away from home in Brazil was <a href="http://www.unir.br">UNIR</a>,
the Federal University of
Rond&ocirc;nia, where I enjoyed tremendous hospitality during my 1996
research trip in the Amazon. I have had the good fortune to return in
2000 and 2003, and am hoping to go back as soon as possible. Visit <b><a
 href="../rondonia.htm">Rondonia Web</a></b> for all of my writings
about the Amazon.<br>
            </td>
            <td><a href="http://www.unir.br"><img src="unir.jpg"
 alt="UNIR" border="0" height="86" width="99"> </a> </td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p><a href="http://www.americas.org/">Resource Center of the
Americas</a> provides news and analysis regarding critical issues
throughout the region. Its extensive database is searchable by topic
and country.</p>
      <p>The Washington Office on Latin America (<a
 href="http://www.wola.org/">WOLA</a>) promotes human rights and
democracy in Latin America, and conducts research on abuses, including
those for which the United States government shares responsibility.<br>
      </p>
      <center>
      <table bgcolor="#ffcc99" cellpadding="5" width="85%">
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>
            <center><a href="http://lanic.utexas.edu/las.html"
 target="body"><img src="lanic.GIF" border="0" height="78" width="284">
            </a> </center>
            <b>Your first stop</b> for Latin American web surfing as
well as serious research should be the Latin American Studies program
at the University of Texas at Austin, which maintains a comprehensive <a
 href="http://lanic.utexas.edu/las.html"> lanic WW Virtual Library</a>
of links related to Latin America, organized by <b>topic</b> and <b>country</b>
. Spend a couple of hours on this site!</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      </center>
      </td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>
<div align="center">
<p>I have been a member of the <a
 href="http://lasa.international.pitt.edu/"> Latin American Studies
Association</a> since 1989. </p>
</div>
<p>The <a href="http://www.azcentral.com/ent/dead/">Day of the Dead</a>
(Dia de los Muertos) is an important tradition in Mexico, and one that
strikes many North Americans as particularly unusual. <br>
&nbsp;
<table border="0" width="100%">
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td><a href="http://www.zmag.org"><img alt="Z-Communications"
 src="zcommlogo.gif"
 style="border: 0px solid ; width: 86px; height: 82px;"></a><a
 href="http://www.zmag.org"><br>
      </a> </td>
      <td>For an unabashedly radical perspectives on Latin America (and
many other topics), go to <a href="http://www.zmag.org">Z-Communications</a>,
the
online
portal for <i>Z</i> magazine and related projects. Yes, radicals do
still exist, and they are still needed. This very well-written magazine
is for
those
who think <i><a href="http://www.TheNation.com/">The Nation</a> </i>
has gotten too stodgy!</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>
</p>
<p>The <a href="http://www.hrw.org/campaigns/chile98/">Pinochet
Prosecution</a> page at Human Rights Watch describes the efforts to
extradite and prosecute the former Chilean dictator, years after he was
taken out of office. Although it may seem ancient history to North
Americans, U.S. support for this tyrant -- and many like him -- is
still remembered in Latin America.<br>
&nbsp;
<table cellpadding="5" width="100%">
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td><a href="http://www.hrw.org/americas/index.php" target="body"
 background-color:="#cc0000"><img src="hrw-logo.gif" nosave=""
 border="0"></a> </td>
      <td>More generally, see the Human Rights Watch <a
 href="http://www.hrw.org/americas/index.php"> Latin America</a> page
for the latest news on human-rights abuses throughout the region. HRW
provides advocacy and research support to the brave grassroots
activists throughout Latin America who are trying to end
politically-motivated assassinations, torture, and disappearances.
Citizens of the U.S. have a responsibility
to become informed about these issues, because the crimes are sometimes
committed on behalf of U.S. corporations or government interests. In
particular,
look on the site for the latest information about the so-called War on
Drugs
in Colombia and elsewhere.</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>
</p>
