 alt="Banana Link" src="bananalink.gif"
 style="border: 0px solid ; width: 103px; height: 101px;"></a><br>
      <div style="text-align: center;"><big><span
 style="font-family: Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif; font-weight: bold; color: rgb(255, 255, 51);"><br>
BANANA</span><br
 style="font-family: Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif; font-weight: bold; color: rgb(255, 255, 51);">
      <big><span
 style="font-family: Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif; font-weight: bold; color: rgb(255, 255, 51);">LINK</span></big></big><br>
      </div>
      </td>
      <td style="vertical-align: top;">To understand many of the
catastrophes that have
befallen Latin America, it is important to understand the role that
U.S. government support of the United Fruit Company has played
throughout the twentieth century. Fortunately, <a
 href="http://www.business.uiuc.edu/mbucheli/">Dr. Marcelo Bucheli</a>
has
document this in many publications, including the article <a
 href="http://www.business.uiuc.edu/Working_Papers/Abstract.asp?PaperID=06-0115">Good
Dictator, Bad Dictator</a> and the book <span
 style="font-style: italic;"><a
 href="http://es.oxfordjournals.org/cgi/content/extract/6/3/512">Bananas
and Business</a>.<br>
      <br>
      </span>It is difficult to overstate the influence of United
Fruit: U.S. military forces often served it as a private army,
enforcing unequal relations within Latin American agriculture and
building generations of resentment. The <a
 href="http://www.unitedfruit.org">United Fruit Historic Society</a>
web site is inactive (as of June 2008), but it provides many resources,
including a bibliography, chronology, and key biographies.<br>
      <br>
Learn more about the industry and what is being done to improve it from
      <a href="http://www.bananalink.org.uk/content/view/10/14/lang,en/">Banana
Link</a>, a fair trade banana cooperative.<br>
      <span style="font-style: italic;"></span></td>
      <td style="vertical-align: top;"><a
 href="http://www.unitedfruit.org"><img alt="United Fruit"
 src="unitedfruit.jpg"
 style="border: 0px solid ; width: 267px; height: 116px;"></a><br>
      </td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>
<br>
<span style="font-style: italic;"></span>
<p><a href="http://boto.ocean.washington.edu/americacentral/"
 target="body"><img src="../GRAPHICS/ambiocentro.jpg"
 alt="Centroamerica - Ambiente" nosave="" align="left" border="0"
 height="127" hspace="5" width="200"> </a> The site Centroamerica
Ecologia y Ambiente (Central America Ecology and Environment) presents
research on Central American environmental matters in both English and
Spanish. This site was recommended by a student in my GEOG 130 course. </p>
<p>The book <i>Pobreza y Medio Ambiente en America Latina </i>is
published by the Centro Interdisciplinario de Estudios sobre el
Desarrollo Latinoamericano (CIEDLA) in Buenos Aires. It provides case
studies of the link between poverty and the environment in seven Latin
American countries. If you are interested in these topics, request the
book from the library.</p>
<table background="brflagbk.gif" cellpadding="10" cols="1" width="100%">
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td><b><font face="Arial,Helvetica"><font color="#009900"><a
 href="http://www.vivabrazil.com/"> Viva Brazil!</a> is a great gateway
site for the country of Brazil. It is operated by Walter T. Morales. I
like
the site because it presents information about Brazil in a geographic
format - organized by major regions and then by states. In some ways, I
think his <a href="http://psg.com/%7Ewalter/brasil.html"> old site</a>
is
even better!</font></font></b></td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>
<p><b><a href="http://www.ibge.gov.br">IBGE</a> </b> is the Brazilian
equivalent of a combined U.S. Census Bureau and Geological Survey. Its
web site -- in Portuguese and English -- has a wealth of information
about the country. If the information transfer is too slow, try the <a
 href="http://www.ibge.org/default.htm"> IBGE mirror site</a> in the
U.S. </p>
<p><b><a href="http://www.brazilmax.com/">BrazilMax</a> </b> "is
designed for gringos who - for whatever reason - have a special
interest in Brasil." It includes literary journalism, investigative
reporting, literature, and scholarly research. It aims to be a cross
between <i>The New Yorker</i> and the <i>UTNE Reader </i>for Brazil.
</p>
<p>Scottish Geographer Kay Williams shares an interest in Brazil, and
provides some <a
 href="http://www.geography.btinternet.co.uk/brazil.htm">useful links</a>
about two of my favorite aspects of the country: the Amazon and the
cities. </p>
Sociologist Ted Goertzel is an authority on Brazilian President
Fernando Enrique Cardoso. His <a
 href="http://crab.rutgers.edu/%7Egoertzel/fhc.htm"> Brazil page</a> is
an essential guide to current national politics and economy in Brazil.
<p> </p>
